This test generates a set of random values for each invocation of recurse(),
continues recursion down to the outermost frame, and then re-uses the values
upon returning.  This tests the runtime's basic ability to copy live values
between the source and destination stack.

Note: this is broken on x86-64 due to instruction scheduling issues

Expected output for default run (note that generated values may change):
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Before values: 4 0 1 -1 4 -6 -6 -6
Before values: 3 5 6 2 0 5 1 0
Before values: 6 2 0 3 2 2 4 3
Before values: 4 5 0 2 5 2 4 4
Before values: 5 6 6 3 3 3 1 3
Before values: 5 3 5 0 1 2 3 3
Before values: 0 0 7 4 7 0 6 5
Before values: 3 7 3 5 2 3 1 5
Before values: 0 5 3 5 0 7 5 1
Before values: 4 4 3 0 1 6 3 0
<timing information>
After values: 4 4 3 0 1 6 3 0
After values: 0 5 3 5 0 7 5 1
After values: 3 7 3 5 2 3 1 5
After values: 0 0 7 4 7 0 6 5
After values: 5 3 5 0 1 2 3 3
After values: 5 6 6 3 3 3 1 3
After values: 4 5 0 2 5 2 4 4
After values: 6 2 0 3 2 2 4 3
After values: 3 5 6 2 0 5 1 0
After values: 4 0 1 -1 4 -6 -6 -6

